docs/pipeline.md describes the data flow and error handling for the steno dictionary compiler: how `dict.steno` moves through five passes (parse, count expansion, type append, line-flag, and render/snippet) to produce four JSON artifacts and an optional C++ header.

The two distinct paths are: (1) **`dict.steno`** → fully enumerated rows via Pass B → `out/{plain,smart}-ts.json` and `out/{snippets,vim-snippets}.json`, and (2) **`dict.infinite.steno`** → two lookup tables (types and constructs) → C++ header, where nesting is unbounded. These cross at parse + Pass A only; Pass B is skipped for the infinite path.

Key load-bearing details: Pass A resolves `@count` fan-out, `%d`, and `%(EXPR)` once; Pass B fills `%t` type slots via append. After Pass B, a whole-batch post-pass (`fix_family_terminals`) re-marks entries as non-terminal if they are strict `/`-prefixes of later entries — this is the only way to detect family roots that `expand_types_one` can't see one-entry-at-a-time. The infinite path's `walk` function must render identical text and terminal flags as Pass B + `fix_family_terminals` for any sequence both can express; this agreement is enforced by differential test (`cpp_check.rs`), not asserted. `@fuse` in the infinite path uses `%T` (fused slot marker); the walker inverts the merge via `subtract_strokes`, and `check_fuse_ambiguity` prevents two `(shape, type)` pairs from colliding.

Snippets emit two maps: `plover-keys` holds non-terminals as unsentineled `{^}…{^}` (so Plover's backspace matches), and terminals as `{^}@@…@@{^}` sentinel-wrapped; `snippets` holds terminal `key_id` → LSP body. Module dataflow is strictly forward (no back-edges). Five error types own specific passes; nothing is swallowed or panics. The editor model factors out keystroke interpretation (`interpret`), movement generation (`movement_events`), and serialization (`serialize`), controlled by a `Behaviors` preset (PLAIN, SMART, SMART_INDENT).